{{refimprove|date=April 2014}} The '''Heatherley School of Fine Art''' is an independent [[art school]] in London.
The school was named after Thomas Heatherley who took over as the school's principal from [[James Mathews Leigh]] (when it was named "Leigh's"). Founded in 1845, the school is affectionately known as Heatherley's. It is one of the oldest independent art schools in London and is among the few art colleges in Britain that focus on portraiture, [[Figurative art|figurative painting]] and sculpture.
It opened a new school, on George Street (off [[Baker Street]]), London, in November 1927 after previously being located on Newman Street.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lord Dewar On Art |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl%2f0000483%2f19271104%2f135 |work=Kent & Sussex Courier |date=4 November 1927 |via=[[British Newspaper Archive]] |accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>
[[William Russell Flint]], [[Solomon Joseph Solomon]], [[Gregoire Boonzaier]], [[Michael Ayrton]] and [[Kate Greenaway]] are numbered amongst its former students as was the first Principal of the [[Slade School of Art]], [[Edward Poynter|Sir Edward Poynter]].
